{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930062401/0168.xml":{"full_text":"18\nM WASHINGTON TIHESFISAHCIAL NEWS HB\n\u2022-T\u2022 -\u2014t\nTechnical Rally in Stocks Will Continue, the Spectator Advises Traders\nf 1* I u e. t. if*.\nRALLY SALES\nADVISED BY\nEXPERT\nRough Stolons Seen for Some\nWith Trend Swinging Both\n.U 0 and Down Daily\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nAs this column is written, we\nrave just recovered from the sur\nprise of witnessing one of the\nsharpest recoveries the Stock\nMarket, has experienced this\nytar, despite the fact that news\nfrom the commodity markets and\nmost other sources was distinctly\nbearish.\nThus we are led to believe\nthat the rally was the result of\nconditions within the market,\nrather than any outside .factor,\nIn brief, many market operators,\nstudents and bankers have con*,\neluded that the market has been\nthoroughly sold out, and a tech\nnical rally is amply justified.\nThe technical rally was fore\ncast in this column Saturday,\nwhen I told traders to buy stocks\naround their lows and sell them\non any rally early this week. I\nbelieve the recovery is likely to\ncarry through today\u2019s session,\nwith occasional dips resulting\nfrom short selling to test the\nstability of the market. At the\nsame time, I think it would be\nthe better part of wisdom for\nthose who bought stocks Satur\nday to sell on any further ad\nvance.\nThe Harvard Statement\nOne of the important reasons\nfor the maintenance of the rally\nyesterday was the statement\nfrom the Harvard Economic So\nciety that an early improvement\nin business is to be expected. It\nwas poiinted out that bearish\nness within the business fold of\nten indicates the initial stages\nof an up-turn in the business\ncurves. With all due respect for\nthe opinion of the society, I ques\ntion whether the opinion of the\nmost conservative Wall Street\nbankers, brokers and stock op\nerators is to be disregarded.\nThe concensus in the financial\ndistrict is that we will see lower\nprices, that the market cannot\nbe expected to begin a sustained\nrecovery until August, and that\nthe only bright spot on the busi\nness horizon that can be dis\ncounted within the next couple\nof months is the Christmas trade.\nGeneral Electric Company has\npassed the year\u2019s production peak,\nwhich may account for some of\nthe selling. 9 However, there is\ngossip that the stock will break\nto ISO a share. .This is not my\nprediction, but I would not advise\ntraders to go long of the stock\nnow. The same goes for Westing\nhouse.\nPan-American Offer\nAs predicted here some time\nago. Standard Oil of Indiana has\nrenewed the exchange offer by\nwhich stockholders of Pan-Ameri\ncan Petroleum and Transport\nCompany would receive seven\nshares of Standard of Indiana\nfor each six shares of their own\nstock. At the present time, Stan\ndard of Indiana owns about 83\nper cent of Pan-American Petro\nleum A and B shares, its holding\nhaving been increased substan\ntially under the exchange offer\nwhich expired last November.\nOne of the factors most con\nducive to renewed strength *at\ntoday\u2019s stock market opening was\nthe rally of all grains, except July\nwheat, at yesterday\u2019s close to\nlevels above Saturday\u2019s close. The\nsteady decline of wheat had been\none of the chief influences tend\ning toward a decline in securities\nmarkets. v\nSteel Support\nIt was obvious all through yes\nterday\u2019s session that the bankers\nand investment groups were de\ntermined to prevent Steel Com\nifton from breaking below the\nprice level of 150, established\nlast November, strong support\nwas thrown into the market when\nSteel touched 152, a new low\nfor the year and that support was\nbasically responbile for the rally\nthat swept prices upward in the\nbest recovery seen in several\nweeks. Steel common* has been\na favorite target of the bears\nlately, their activities being en\ncouraged by knowledge that those\nclosest to the corporation man\nagement had liquidated their hold\nings near the year\u2019s highest\nSices. Realizing, however, that\ne market would be smashed\nif Steel broke its 1920 low. its\nsponsors gave it the best kind\nof support. It is quite possible\nthat this support may mark the\nbeginning of the reaccumulation\nwhich, it has been predicted, will\nsignal the start of the next \u201cbull\nmarket.**\nThe street\u2019s largest wire house\nrecently cut its margin require\nments but this simply meant plac\ning them on parity With those ot\nthe other large houses. In gen\nenral there is a disposition to\ntighten margin requirements and\nDepart!\n\u25a0r j JU\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nHAROLD D. KRAFT\nGENERAL AGENT in Wash\nington for the State Mutual\nLife Assurance Co., of Wor\ncester, Mass., who left yesterday i\nevening for the convention of\nthat company at Old Point\nComfort, Va.\nroiriMi\nMAKES OFFER\nNEW YORK, June 24.\u2014 Direc\ntors of the Standard Oil Company\nof Indiana today voted to renew\nthe offer to stockholders of Pan\nAmerican Petroleum and Transit\nCompany for the exchange of\nstock on a basis of seven shares\nof Indiana for six shares of Pan\nAmerican. The offer was renewed\nfor a period of July 1 to August\n15, inclusive.\nEdward G. Seubert, president of\nthe Standard, said the offer was\nmade because of many requests\nfrom Pan American stockholders\nwho were unable to exchange\ntheir stock during the period of\nthe previous exchange offer, which\nexpired on November 30, last year.\nStandard of Indiana now owns\n93 per cent of the Class \u201cA\u201d stock,\n79 per cent of the Class \u201cB\u201d and\n83 per cent of the common stock\nof the Pan American company.\nAnnouncement was made also\ntoday of a drive to retire the\nfractional shares of Standard of\nIndiana, of which nearly 20,000\nare outstanding, on which the\ncost of administration is out of\nproportion to their value.\nBuch shares will be bought! at\na rate of 856 a share, or in case\nholders want to buy enough to\ncomplete \u2019a whole share, fractions\nwould be sold to them on the\nsame basis.\nIn the Indiana-Pan American\nExchange fractions involved will\nbe settled for in cash, or on a\nbasis of 856 for Indiana and 865\nfor Pan American, so that no\nfractional shares will result from\nthe transactions.\nTennessee 4 1 2 b Due\nOn Market Today\nNEW YORK. June 24 (U.S.).\nKean, Taylor Co., Ames. Em\nerich Co., Inc., and C. F. Childs\nCo., Inc., are offering 8500,000\nState of Tennessee 4% per cent\nbonds, due July 1, 1945. The\nbonds are priced to yield 4JO per\ncent.\nThey are issued for University\nof Tennessee building purposes\nand are direct and general obliga\ntions of the StatO of Tennessee,\npayable for unlimited ad valorem\ntaxer.\nit is difficult to find a firm that\nwill carry low-priced shares on\nmarg'\nTobacco Shares\nAmerican Tobacco Company an\nnounces that May sales of its\nmost popular cigarette gained\n558,000,000, bringing the gain for\nthe first five months of the year\nto 2,384,000,000 over the corres\nponding period of last year. All\nof which is In line with my pre\ndictions that cigarette production\ncompanies would show the best\nrecords forthcoming from any in\ndustry. Various explanations are\noffered for the huge gain in\ncigarette consumption. On the\nsurface, some of them are face\ntious, but, on second thought,\nthey sound quite logical. It has\nbeen remarked that thousands of\nfactory employes who cannot\nsmoke while working are out of\nwork now and have nothing to\ndo but worry and smoke. It is\nalso pointed out that nervous\nWall Street traders help to swell\ncigarette consumption these days\nby lighting one \u201cbutt\u201d from an\nother. At any rate, American\nTobacco Company and its chief\ncompetitors continue to earn large\nprofits. It is reported that Ameri\ncan Tobacco will split its shares\nthree for one before many\nmonths have passed, assuming,\nof course, that the course of the\nmarket does not save the direc\ntors the trouble. 7\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\ni\u2022\nLIFE INSURANCE\nAMOUNT IS\nPROBLEM\nPolicies Should Be Considered\nSavings and Not Expense,\nExpert Points Out\nBy FRANK F. LOOMIS\nOne of the great problems the\naverage business man has to\nsolve is how much life insurance\nhe should carry and what can\nhe afford to pay for it.\nLife insurance should not be\nfigured as an expense as it is\npurely a savings proposition\ncoupled with an absolute safety\nclause for the protection of the\nman\u2019s family in case of death\nand a savings for himself in ma\nture years.\nA lump sum of money is often\na dangerous thing to leave to a\nman\u2019s family as the principal\nmay be squandered, or lost\nthrough unfortunate investments.\nA monthly life income is the an\nswer to this problem.\nIf you wish to know just what\nthe monthly Income will be if\nyour Insurance is payable in that\nmanner, instead of in a lump\nsum, first, set down the total\namount of life insurance you\nnow have, whether it is 81,000,\n82,000, 85,000 or 850,000. Second,\nscratch out the last two ciphers.\nThird, divide the number that\nremains by two. Your answer is\nthe amount of monthly income\nfrom your life insurance you are\nleaving to your wife or de\npendents when you die. This\nresult may show that you are\npossibly over-insured or that you\nare not carrying enough life in\nsurance.\nAnother simple way to figure\nhow much life insurance you\nshould carry is as follows: If the\ninterest on your life policy, plus\nthe income on your other invest\nments, will equal one-half of your\npresent income and earnings, you\ndo not need any more life insur\nance. If it does not, then you\ndo need more as surely you want*\nto leave your family an income\nafter your death of at least one\nhalf of what it is now. Your\nearnings will stop at your death\nbut so will i your personal ex\npenses. Therefore, 50 per cent is\na safe amount to figure on.\nIn explanation, supposing your\nincome from securities is 82,000\nand your salary 810,000 and you\ndesire to leave your family at\nyour death one-half of your\npresent income, which would be\n86,000. As your securities would\npay 82,000, you should carry\nenough life insurance to yield\n84,000 a year more.\nThere are close to 10,000,000\nwomen in the United States who\nearn their own living. Hundreds\nof thousands are employed as\nstenographers, typists, secretaries.\nIn the school teaching profession,\n78 per cent are women. The\nGovernment offices employ large\nnumbers of women and the\ntelephone industry is one of the\nlargest users of women labor. In\nthe department stores, there are\nthousands of women clerks and\nalso in the factories, mills and\nindustries. A very small propor\ntion of these working women\ncarry either life, health or\naccident insurance. And they\nare dependent on their earnings\nfor a living and in many cases\nhave a family also to support.\nFor the business woman, a 20-\nyear endowment policy is an ex\ncellent form. This policy costs, at\nage 35, about 845 a year for 81.000,\npayable at death, at any time, or\nin cash at the end of 20 yean.\nThen\u2014her ihcome must be pro\ntected! An accident and health\npolicy, paying a stipulated sum\nweekly in case of illness or acci\ndent, will protect her earnings\nagainst loss, which is essential to\n\u2022the self-supporting woman.\nThe First National Studio re\ncently took out an insurance\npolicy of 81.000,000 on the speak\ning voice of Corrlne Griffith, mov\ning picture star. Miss Griffith, in\ncommenting on the importance of\ninsurance, makes the following\nstatement:\n\u201cInsurance has certainly\nplayed a great part in helping\nto make America the meet pros\nperous country In the world. It.\nteaches thrift; it safeguards the\nwelfare of the family; it en\nables Individuals to enjoy the\ncomforts of life in their old\nage; it is a protection against\nfinancial loss through accident\nor ill-health and it has a dozen\nother important advantages\ndVer the usual ways of saving.\nIn the motion picture world, in\nsurance is recognised as invalu\nable to the individual players,\nas well as to the company, but\nin various walks of life men\nand women are prone to neg\nlect or overlook the many ad\nt vantages of taking out a policy,\nand they are uncertain as to\njust, what type of policy would\nbe beet suited to their individ\nt ual needs. That is why I be\nHove that the great amount of\neducational publicity which ta\ni surance to receiving through\nthe press win prove of great\nbenefit toths pnNta.**\nElectricity Demand\nOs Railroads Making\nProblems, Is Report\nIncreasing demand for electric\npower with which to operate de\nvices designed to add to the\nsafety and comfort of passengers,\nis providing a problem as to how\nto furnish sufficient electricity on\npassenger trains at ajl times to\nmeet requirements, .according to a\nreport submitted today to the\neleventh annual convention of the\nmechanical division of the Ameri\ncan Railway Association.\nBefore the advent of electric\nrefrigeration, cigarette lighten,\npressing irons, radios, electric\nwater coolers and heaters, and\nvarious other equipment requir\ning electrical current, sufficient\npower could be generated on each\npassenger car by means of an\nBRITISH FIRMS\nMERGED\nLONDON, June 24 (UJB.).\nMontagu Norman, governor of\nthe Bank of England, today is\nvirtually steel king of Great\nBritain.\nBritain\u2019s steel industry was on\nthe verge of collapse and the\nBank of England stepped in to\narrange a merger of the big steel\ncorporations with a combined\ncapital of nearly 850,000,000. The\nbank will hold the majority of\nvotes.\nThe companies In the merger\nare: Pearson Sb Knowles Coal Sb\nIron Co M Ltd.; Moss Hall Coal\nCo.. Wigan Junction Colliery Co.,\nWigan Coal Sb Iron Co., and Part\nington Steel Iron Co.\nConsidered\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furnisbed by W B Hibbs A Co.)\nSALES\nCapital Traction ss, 85000\n90%, 81,000091.\nGeorgetown Gas ss, 85000101%.\nPotomac Electr